#
# ╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║  REVDOKU CONFIGURATION — READ THIS FIRST                                  ║
# ╠═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╣
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║  You are looking at the TEMPLATE file: env.example                        ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║  Before Revdoku can start, you must:                                      ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║  1. Make a COPY of this file in the same folder, and name the copy        ║
# ║     exactly:                                                              ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║         .env.local                                                        ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║     YES — the file name starts with a DOT and has NO EXTENSION.           ║
# ║     (On macOS / Linux, names starting with a dot are "hidden", so         ║
# ║     you may need to enable "Show hidden files" in your file browser       ║
# ║     to see it. From a terminal, `ls -la` shows everything.)               ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║     From a terminal opened inside this folder:                            ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║         cp env.example .env.local                                         ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║  2. Open the new .env.local file in any text editor and fill in every     ║
# ║     line marked [REQUIRED] below.                                         ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║  3. Start Revdoku:                                                        ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║         ./bin/start                                                       ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║  Do NOT edit this env.example file itself — it is a template and          ║
# ║  Revdoku does not read it. Revdoku only reads the .env.local file you     ║
# ║  create in step 1.                                                        ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ║  Variables not listed here use sensible defaults.                         ║
# ║                                                                           ║
# ╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
#


# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#                            [REQUIRED] SECTION
#
#   These variables are REQUIRED. Revdoku will refuse to start if any of
#   them is blank. Fill them all in before running `./bin/start`.
#
#   ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
#   │  ⚠  SECURITY WARNING — USE A DIFFERENT, UNIQUE RANDOM VALUE FOR      │
#   │     EACH OF THE FOUR SECRETS BELOW:                                  │
#   │                                                                      │
#   │         SECRET_KEY_BASE                                              │
#   │         LOCKBOX_MASTER_KEY                                           │
#   │         PREFIX_ID_SALT                                               │
#   │         REVDOKU_DOC_API_KEY                                          │
#   │                                                                      │
#   │     NEVER reuse the same string across any two of them. Each one     │
#   │     protects a different layer (session signing, data encryption,    │
#   │     public-URL hashing, inter-service auth). Reusing a value leaks   │
#   │     one layer's guarantees into the next — e.g. anyone who can read  │
#   │     the URL salt can also decrypt your database if it matches the    │
#   │     Lockbox key.                                                     │
#   │                                                                      │
#   │     Run `openssl rand -hex 32` (or `-hex 64` for SECRET_KEY_BASE)    │
#   │     separately for EACH variable. Copy/paste mistakes are the most   │
#   │     common cause of accidental reuse — double-check.                 │
#   └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [REQUIRED] SECRET_KEY_BASE
#
# Rails uses this to sign session cookies. Changing it later logs everyone out.
# Generate a fresh random value by running this in a terminal:
#
#     openssl rand -hex 64
#
# Paste the output after the = sign (no quotes, no spaces).
# ⚠  Must be UNIQUE — do NOT reuse the value you picked for any other secret.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SECRET_KEY_BASE=146c6a78cfcdcf7cbe58044d639d48b69b855cb0d08f610a5da5ff9d106b376cd6f9a3be32fa18d266ed584a1cb5bb2c3deb7485b7ea82daaadbcb985c7af566


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [REQUIRED] LOCKBOX_MASTER_KEY
#
# Encrypts every sensitive field Revdoku stores (user 2FA seeds, API tokens,
# envelope titles, checklist rules, report bodies). Losing or changing this
# value makes all encrypted data permanently unreadable — STORE IT SAFELY
# (password manager, secrets vault, etc.).
#
# Generate:
#
#     openssl rand -hex 32
#
# ⚠  Must be UNIQUE — do NOT reuse SECRET_KEY_BASE / PREFIX_ID_SALT / DOC_API_KEY.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
LOCKBOX_MASTER_KEY=f329fcaeacccb86ae3d1e297e65d18d9041a7d0d8c56e7906efca8fa59e6d245


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [REQUIRED] PREFIX_ID_SALT
#
# Seeds the short public IDs Revdoku uses in URLs (like env_abc123, rpt_xyz).
# Changing it after launch changes every URL and breaks bookmarks / links
# already shared with others.
#
# Generate:
#
#     openssl rand -hex 32
#
# ⚠  Must be UNIQUE — do NOT reuse SECRET_KEY_BASE / LOCKBOX_MASTER_KEY / DOC_API_KEY.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PREFIX_ID_SALT=ef807fc10141772294e36ac07d5bfb0190ebcb4c21083243ea8392afacf33fd3


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [REQUIRED] REVDOKU_DOC_API_KEY
#
# An internal password between Revdoku's Rails app and its document-processing
# service. Both run inside the same container, so this value never leaves your
# machine. Any long random string works — it's only read at startup.
#
# Generate:
#
#     openssl rand -hex 32
#
# ⚠  Must be UNIQUE — do NOT reuse SECRET_KEY_BASE / LOCKBOX_MASTER_KEY / PREFIX_ID_SALT.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
REVDOKU_DOC_API_KEY=98d24df8b282bd6f686335ee14bb49657608aefe399383030d4a1ee05eb90645


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [REQUIRED] REVDOKU_BOOTSTRAP_ADMIN_EMAIL
# [REQUIRED] REVDOKU_BOOTSTRAP_ADMIN_PASSWORD
#
# Your first login. Revdoku creates this user as an admin the first time it
# boots, then re-uses it on every subsequent boot (no duplicates).
#
#   - Use a real email address — password-reset + outbound emails go there.
#   - Password must be at least 8 characters.
#
# You can remove these two lines after your first successful login; the
# user persists in the database.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
REVDOKU_BOOTSTRAP_ADMIN_EMAIL=admin@example.com
REVDOKU_BOOTSTRAP_ADMIN_PASSWORD=12345678


# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#                            AI PROVIDER KEYS
#
#   Revdoku needs at least one AI provider key (OpenRouter, OpenAI, Anthropic,
#   Google, AWS Bedrock) to run document inspections. You have two options —
#   pick whichever fits your workflow. Per-account keys (BYOK) are preferred
#   on a multi-user install; env keys are simpler for a single-user box.
#
#   ── Option 1 (preferred): BYOK, configured inside the app ───────────────
#   After signing in, go to  Account → AI → Providers  and paste your key
#   there. Revdoku encrypts it per-account in the database and keeps it out
#   of the shell environment. Per-account keys take precedence over the
#   env-var fallbacks below — so you can leave the env vars empty/unset and
#   still run inspections via BYOK.
#
#   ── Option 2: operator-wide env keys (fallback) ─────────────────────────
#   Uncomment any of the lines below and paste your key. Names follow the
#   pattern  <PROVIDER>_API_KEY  (no prefix — these are the same names the
#   Rails resolver and doc-api both read directly from the environment).
#   Leave a line UNSET (commented out) to disable a provider. Setting a line
#   to an empty value (e.g.  OPENROUTER_API_KEY=  ) is treated as "not
#   configured" and logs a warning at boot — either fill it in or remove it.
# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# OPENROUTER_API_KEY=
# OPENAI_API_KEY=
# ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=
# GOOGLE_CLOUD_API_KEY=
# AWS_BEDROCK_API_KEY=
# AWS_BEDROCK_BASE_URL=


# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#                            [OPTIONAL] SECTION
#
#   Everything below this line has a sensible default. You can ignore all
#   of it on first run and come back later to customize.
# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [OPTIONAL] REVDOKU_LOGIN_MODE  (default: password_no_confirmation)
#
# How new accounts sign up:
#   password_no_confirmation — email + password, no email-confirmation step.
#                              Best for single-user / airgapped / internal use.
#   password                 — email + password + email confirmation. Requires
#                              working SMTP (see below) or users can't confirm.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
REVDOKU_LOGIN_MODE=password_no_confirmation


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [OPTIONAL] SMTP — outbound email
#
# Only needed if REVDOKU_LOGIN_MODE=password (email confirmation), for
# password-reset emails, or for account invitations. Skip this section if
# you're using password_no_confirmation on a single-user install.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SMTP_SERVER=smtp.example.com
# SMTP_PORT=587
# SMTP_USERNAME=
# SMTP_PASSWORD=
# SMTP_DOMAIN=


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [OPTIONAL] REVDOKU_PORT  (default: 3000)
#
# Which port on your machine Revdoku listens on. Visit
# http://localhost:<this-port>/ after `./bin/start`.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# REVDOKU_PORT=3000


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [OPTIONAL] REVDOKU_FORCE_SSL  (default: off)
#
# Turn on HTTPS-only mode. Only set to true when you've put a TLS-terminating
# reverse proxy (nginx, Caddy, Cloudflare, Traefik, etc.) in front of this
# container. With force_ssl on and no TLS in front, the browser will refuse
# to connect because the app 301-redirects every HTTP request to https://.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# REVDOKU_FORCE_SSL=true


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [OPTIONAL] APP_HOST + APP_PROTOCOL  (default: http://localhost)
#
# The public hostname + scheme Revdoku uses when it writes links back into
# itself (confirmation emails, password-reset links, etc.). Change both
# once you're running behind TLS on a real domain.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# APP_HOST=your.domain.example
# APP_PROTOCOL=https


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [OPTIONAL] File storage  (default: local Docker volume)
#
# By default, uploaded documents are saved inside a Docker volume named
# `revdoku_storage`. Zero setup, works for single-host installs. Be careful:
# running `docker compose down -v` DELETES the volume and WIPES all uploads.
#
# For off-host storage (multi-host deploys, external backups), set
# ACTIVE_STORAGE_SERVICE=amazon and fill in the AWS_* block. Works with real
# AWS S3 or any S3-compatible service (MinIO, Cloudflare R2, Backblaze B2,
# DigitalOcean Spaces) via the AWS_S3_ENDPOINT override.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ACTIVE_STORAGE_SERVICE=amazon
# AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
# AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
# AWS_REGION=us-east-1
# AWS_S3_BUCKET=
# AWS_S3_ENDPOINT=          # only for S3-compatible services; leave blank for real AWS


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [OPTIONAL] REVDOKU_IMAGE  (default: the official ghcr.io image)
#
# Override the container image pulled by `docker compose`. Useful for forks
# that publish their own build to a different GHCR owner.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# REVDOKU_IMAGE=ghcr.io/your-org/revdoku-app:latest


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# [OPTIONAL] Legal / policy URLs shown in the footer
#
# Point each of these at your OWN Terms / Privacy / Security pages. Each is
# individually optional — a URL is only shown when it's set. When none of
# the four are set, the footer renders a neutral open-source attribution
# link to the Revdoku GitHub repo instead (so end users don't click a
# "Terms" link that 404s or leads to an unrelated policy).
#
# These URLs should NOT point to Revdoku's hosted-cloud policies at
# revdoku.com — those govern the SaaS service, not your self-hosted
# instance. Host your own, or skip them and let the OSS attribution show.
# A starter template lives in docs/LEGAL_TEMPLATE.md.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# REVDOKU_TERMS_URL=https://yourcompany.com/terms
# REVDOKU_PRIVACY_URL=https://yourcompany.com/privacy
# REVDOKU_SOURCE_CODE_URL=https://github.com/revdoku/revdoku
